1.5.1	More important than tracking the intruder, is to stop the intruder from continuing to access your network.	St
1.5.2	The first thing you need to do is dump WEP.	St
1.5.3	WEP is hiddeously insecure and can be, and (as you found out) frequently is, trivially hacked.	St
1.5.4	In fact, the FBI did it in 3 minutes using Kismet, Airodump, Airplay, and Aircrack.	St
1.5.5	The proccess is not very complicated, and the above listed tools are readily available.	St
1.5.6	You really need to move to WPA2 if your equiptment will support it, or at least WPA, with a randomly generated sufficient complex passphrase.	St
1.5.7	Now the bad news, WPA/WPA2 has a vulnerability as well.	St
1.5.8	You do not want to use a short passphrase consisting of a word found in the dictionary.	St
1.5.9	This will leave you vulnerable to an offline dictionary attack (A type of brute force attack where words found in the dictionary are thrown against a passprase to recover the passphrase) by someone using KisMac or coWPAtty.	St
1.5.10	(Two popular wireless hacking tools that are also freely available) You will want to use a randomly generated complex passphrase consisting of at least 34 characters.	St
1.5.11	Most publications say 20 characters, but you get about 2.5n bits of security per character +12 bits (2.5n+12 total) in a passphrase.	St
1.5.12	So, this would only give you 62 bits of equivelent security.	St
1.5.13	Bare minimum you want want 96 bits of security, so 34 characters will give you a total 97 bits.	St
1.5.14	Ideally, you will want to use a 64 digit hexadecimal.	St
1.5.15	This will give you a full 256 bits of security, plus using a 64 digit hex avoids the hashing process used to create the 256 bit Pairwise Master Key, because the hex is used directly as the key.	St
1.5.16	It is this hashing process (Specifically, the MIC hash value)that leaves WPA/WPA2 vulnerable to a dictionary attack when short dictionary words are used as the passphrase.	St
1.5.17	Now the good news.	St
1.5.18	The brute force dictionary attack is the only known effective attack against WPA/WPA2.	St
1.5.19	if you use a 64 digit hex you will make your network reasonably secure against any sort of brute force attack in that each of the 2^256 possibilities must be tried since your passphrase can not be found in a dictionary.	St
