1.5.23	Now the best news of all.	St
1.5.24	The DES cracker Deep Crack (something your local wardriver is not likely to have) could only do 90 billion keys a second,and would take 4.0769221021355023274397357709461x10^58 years to exhaust all the possibilities.	St
1.5.25	Newer devices can do 256 billion keys a second These computing Goliaths (something your local wardriver is even less likely to have) would still take 1.4332929265320125369905321069732x10^58 years to exhaust the possibilities.	St
1.5.26	The two most popular tools, KisMac and coWPAtty (something your local wardriver IS likely to have) can do 100 and 60 keys per second respectively.	St
1.5.27	Now, this can actually be subtantially increased to around 76,000 keys a second using precomputed hashes and very large dictionary files (again, readily available).	St
1.5.28	But, 76,000 still falls way short of even the DES cracker, and precomputed hashes in a dictionary attack are of no use if your SSID hash is not in the hash file, and your password is not in the dictionary file.	St
1.5.29	But, for the sake of argument it would still take 4.8279340683183580193365292024362x10^64 years to run through all the possibilities.	St
1.5.30	In reality at 100 possibilities per second it would take 3.6692298919219520946957621938515x10^67 years to exhaust the possibilities.	St
1.5.31	So as you can see if you use a sufficiently complex and random passphrase, you can have a fairly secure network.	St
